<p>The <b>vertical surface</b> can be used to make to make melodies and basslines. </p>
<p>It's like a fretboard or keyboard, but with the out-of-key notes removed. 
You don't need to know anything about music to get going.</p>

<h3><a target="_out" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VfveFUJXNfo">WATCH: Video Tutorial on the Vertical Surface</a></h3>

<h3>Vertical Surface Tips</h3>
<ul>
<li>The surface is divided horizontally by note pitch.</li>
<li>The lowest notes are at the bottom.</li>
<li>The root note of the key has a grey accent.</li>
<li>The surface is divided vertically by note length.</li>
<li>From left to right:</li>
    <ul>
        <li>Quarter Note</li>
        <li>Eigth Note</li>
        <li>Sixteenth Note</li>
        <li>However long you hold it</li>
    </ul>
<li>To make a string of quarter notes on a <b>C</b> note, click on the far 
left column of the surface on a row (or fret) labeled "C".</li>
<li>The surface supports <b>multi-touch</b> to make arppegios. </li>
<li>In <b>edit mode</b>, you can select notes to change or remove.</li>
<li>Drag notes up and down to change their pitch in <b>edit mode</b>.</li>
<li>With a touchscreen, use two fingers to move the frets up and down in <b>zoom mode.</b>
<li>With a mouse, click and pull toward the top or bottom of the surface.</li>
</ul>
